        "title": "God gives the gift but withholds the capacity to enjoy it — the central irony (6:1-2)",
        "range": "6:1-2",
        "excerpt": "A man to whom God has given riches and wealth and honor so that his soul lacks nothing of all that he desires; yet God has not empowered him to eat from them.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with Qohelet's characteristic observation formula: 'There is an evil which I have seen under the sun.' He has used this construction before (4:1; 5:13), always to introduce something that does not fit the tidy categories of conventional wisdom. What follows in 6:2 is maximally disruptive: a man who has received the entire package of covenant-era blessing — riches (*osher*), wealth (*nekhes*), honor (*kavod*) — in whom 'his soul lacks nothing of all that he desires,' and yet who cannot eat from any of it.\n\nThe theological weight falls on the double occurrence of *Elohim* in verse 2. God gave the wealth; God has not empowered (*shalat*) the man to enjoy it. The same divine agent who bestows is the one who withholds the corresponding capacity. This is not the misfortune of a robbed man or the consequence of a sinful choice; it is sovereign divine prerogative operating in a way that defies simple correlation with either merit or punishment. Tremper Longman III (*The Book of Ecclesiastes*, NICOT) notes that this is one of the most theologically unsettling moments in the entire book precisely because Qohelet will not supply a theodicy. He names the category and moves on.\n\nThe foreigner (*ish nokri*, a stranger) who enjoys what the owner cannot is a figure of reversal that resonates with Deuteronomy 28:33 — the curse of covenant unfaithfulness included enemies consuming one's produce. But Qohelet is not making that connection explicitly. He uses the foreigner-as-beneficiary to sharpen the irony: even the man's enjoyment is displaced. Someone is enjoying the gift; it is simply not the one to whom it was given.\n\nThe pastoral application in the New Testament fills in what Qohelet cannot supply from under the sun. Paul's testimony in Philippians 4:11-13 — 'I have learned, in whatever state I am, to be content... I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me' — names what the man of 6:2 lacks: a capacity that comes not from circumstance but from divine empowerment through union with Christ. The same God who withholds the capacity in 6:2 grants it in a new mode through the Spirit (1 Timothy 6:6-8: 'godliness with contentment is great gain').\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalat* (empowered, v.2) — to have authority or mastery over, to be given dominion. It is the verb used in Genesis 1:28 of human dominion over the earth. The irony is acute: the man who has everything lacks *shalat* over his own possessions. *Osher, nekhes, kavod* — the triad of prosperity, moveable wealth, and social honor is virtually identical to the gifts God promised Solomon in 1 Kings 3:13. Qohelet is describing a Solomonic endowment from which the enjoyment has been removed."
