        "title": "The stillborn surpasses the unsatisfied man — the inversion of blessing (6:3-6)",
        "range": "6:3-6",
        "excerpt": "If a man fathers a hundred children and lives many years... but his soul is not satisfied with good things... I say, 'Better the miscarriage than he.'",
        "body": "Qohelet now runs his case study through extreme hypotheticals. A hundred children in the ancient world was the acme of patriarchal blessing — Abraham's descendants 'as numerous as the stars' (Genesis 15:5), the anxiety of barrenness that runs through the matriarchal narratives, the honor of the man 'whose quiver is full' (Psalm 127:5). Many years compounded the blessing — long life in Deuteronomy 28 was the sign of covenant faithfulness. Yet Qohelet loads both maximally and then removes the one variable that makes either mean anything: satisfaction of soul (*nephesh*). The man who has a hundred children, many years, but no satisfaction, and who does not even receive a proper burial — the ultimate indignity in the ancient world, as the Philistines desecrating Saul's body illustrates (1 Samuel 31:8-13) — is worse off than a stillborn.\n\nThe stillborn (*nephel*, the only occurrence of this term in Ecclesiastes) is presented in a remarkable way. It comes in *hevel* (vapor) and departs into *choshekh* (darkness); its name is covered in obscurity; it never sees the sun and never knows anything. By every measure, its existence is less than the rich unsatisfied man's. Yet the Preacher delivers his verdict: 'it has more rest (*nachat*).' The word *nachat* appears elsewhere in Ecclesiastes at 4:6, where 'one hand full of rest is better than two fists full of labor and striving after wind.' Rest is the chapter's quietly positive pole — not pleasure, not honor, not longevity, but the untroubled cessation of striving after what cannot be obtained.\n\nThe rhetorical question of 6:6 closes the section with leveling force: 'Do not all go to one place?' The 'one place' is death (cf. 3:20 where the same phrase refers to the common destiny of man and animal). No matter how extreme the hypothetical — a thousand years twice over — the destination is fixed. Duration does not alter the structural problem, and it does not change the destination.\n\nChristian readers must hold this passage in canonical tension. Qohelet is not wrong within his frame — he is exhaustively right about 'under the sun.' But the New Testament's 'one place' is not only death; it is resurrection. The same death that levels all in Ecclesiastes 6:6 is the doorway through which Christ passed and to which He attached a new destination: 'I am the resurrection and the life' (John 11:25). The stillborn's 'one place' is not the final word in a canon that includes 1 Corinthians 15.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nephel* (stillborn, v.3) — used only here in Ecclesiastes; cf. Psalm 58:8, where the stillborn is an image of swift, early disappearance. *Nachat* (rest, v.5) — a state of settled quiet; used in Ruth 3:1 of Naomi's concern that Ruth find 'rest' (security, settlement). *Maqom echad* (one place, v.6) — the same phrase as 3:20, which explicitly names that place: 'all came from the dust and all return to the dust.' Qohelet's leveler is physical mortality."
