        "excerpt": "All a man's labor is for his mouth and yet the appetite is not satisfied.",
        "body": "Verse 7 is the chapter's most concentrated diagnosis. *Amal* (labor, toil) is Ecclesiastes' word for the painful, wearisome effort of human work (1:3; 2:10-11, 18-20; 4:8). All of it — every productive human activity — is aimed at *peh* (the mouth), the symbol of immediate, bodily need that can be addressed by provision. Yet the *nephesh* is not filled (*male*). The mouth and the *nephesh* are not the same aperture. Labor can supply the mouth; it cannot supply what the *nephesh* actually hungers for.\n\nThis diagnosis underlies Jesus's encounter with the woman at the well (John 4:13-14): 'Everyone who drinks of this water will thirst again; but whoever drinks of the water that I will give him shall never thirst.' Jesus names precisely the structural problem of Ecclesiastes 6:7 — horizontal provision (the well, the food, the labor) addresses the body but leaves the deeper thirst untouched. The water He offers originates above the sun.\n\nVerse 8 draws the inference: if the fundamental appetite cannot be filled by labor, then neither wisdom nor savvy poverty confers lasting advantage. The wise man (*chakham*) and the fool (*kesil*) are leveled — both eat and are unfulfilled; both toil and arrive at the same destination. The poor man who 'knows how to walk before the living' — who navigates social protocol wisely, who reads the room, who survives by social intelligence — gains nothing more lasting than the fool who does not. The leveling is systematic.\n\nVerse 9 then offers the chapter's most practically usable word: 'What the eyes see is better than what the soul desires (*halakh nephesh*).' The phrase *halakh nephesh* is literally 'the walking of the soul' — restless, roving desire that goes from object to object without settling. The present tense of sight, the concreteness of what is already in hand, is better than the soul's chronic wandering toward what is not yet possessed. This is not fatalism; it is the wisdom of contentment — the same wisdom Paul names in Philippians 4:11 as something 'learned,' not natural. Qohelet commends the posture without being able to name its Source.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Peh* (mouth, v.7) — body-oriented, addressable by material provision. *Nephesh* (soul/appetite, v.7) — the whole desiring self; cannot be filled by what fills the mouth. *Halakh nephesh* (the wandering/walking of desire, v.9) — the restless locomotion of unanchored craving. The participle *halakh* (walking/going) used of the *nephesh* is Qohelet's picture of the soul as a wanderer — cf. 1:4-7, where rivers run to the sea and the sea is never full; wind circuits without purpose. The unsatisfied soul is another circuit in that futility system."
