        "excerpt": "Whatever exists has already been named, and it is known what man is; for he cannot dispute with him who is stronger than he is.",
        "body": "Verses 10-11 are among the most theologically compressed in the chapter. Qohelet makes three claims in rapid succession: (1) whatever exists has already been named; (2) it is known what man is; (3) he cannot dispute with one stronger than he. The three move from cosmological order to anthropological fixity to creaturely impotence.\n\nThe 'naming' (*shem*) of things in the Old Testament is the act of sovereign authority. God names the light, the darkness, and the expanse (Genesis 1:5, 8, 10); Adam names the creatures as their steward under God (Genesis 2:19-20); the naming of a person marks one's relation to them (God renames Abram, Jacob, Solomon). For Qohelet to say 'whatever exists has already been named' is to say the creation order is an accomplished fact, determined by prior divine decree, not an open project the creature can renegotiate. The present moment is not a fresh negotiation; it is the outworking of a settled, divinely authored structure.\n\n'It is known what man is' parallels the first claim. *Adam* — the creature formed from the ground (*adamah*) — is a known quantity. His creatureliness, his mortality, his structural dependence are not hidden variables; they are established features of the creation order. The creature who tries to dispute (*din*, to litigate or contend) with 'one stronger than he' is not just likely to lose; he is attempting something outside his competence. Calvin saw in this verse the foundation of creaturely humility — not servility, but the accurate recognition of one's position in the order of being.\n\nVerse 11 presses the implication: 'the more words, the more futility.' If the creature cannot litigate his way out of creaturely limits, then the proliferation of philosophical or rhetorical words aimed at overcoming those limits increases *hevel* rather than diminishing it. This is a direct rebuke of the human instinct to talk one's way past death, past unsatisfied appetite, past the unanswered double-question of 6:12. The New Testament's answer does not come through more discourse but through an event — the resurrection of Jesus Christ, which addresses the 'one place' of 6:6 from outside the sun's frame.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kevar* (already, v.10) — Qohelet's marker of the established past, used in 1:10; 2:12, 16; 3:15; 4:2 to press the fixity of the present order. Things are as they are because they were already determined. *Din* (dispute/litigate, v.10) — a legal term; the creature attempting to bring God to court. The same legal metaphor runs through Job's complaint and God's reply from the whirlwind (Job 38-41)."
